commit_message:
Implement an indexed ResourceClass Enum object

A ResourceClass is a type describing entities which provide consumable
resources to the environment. Later patches will implement resource
providers, pools, inventories and allocations. These providers will be
restricted to those types which are listed in the Enum.

This is a modified Enum that provides a way to have the ResourceClass be
static but also provide an int to be used as a logical foreign key in
the persistence scenarios in which instances of resource providers will
be in the data store. The int is the index into the enum.

Given a ResourceClass its index can be accessed via the 'index'
classmethod. 'from_index' is used to go the other way.

Change-Id: I7ce17347056b0fd2122885e556e03d6530bc2469
Implements: blueprint resource-classes

commit_message:
Accept token and tenant_id for authenticating against KS

Allow swiftclient to authenticate against keystone using tenant
name/id and token only. Without this patch, the password is
required, which may not always be available. Authentication
against keystone is required to get the service catalog,
which includes the endpoints for swift.

Change-Id: I4477af445474c5fa97ff864c4942f1330b59e5d6
Closes-Bug: #1476002

commit_message:
Get a ReqSpec in evacuate API and pass it to scheduler

Since the RequestSpec object is now persisted in the API layer every time that
we start an instance, we can now fetch it from the API DB and pass it thru the
ComputeTask API to the conductor so it can directly call the scheduler with it.

NOTE(sbauza): Yeah, it's ugly to see the ReqsSpec object being dehydrated to
legacy dicts and then rehydrated by the next call, but I'll modify that in my
next change.

Partially-Implements: blueprint check-destination-on-migrations

Change-Id: I7fe694175bb47f53d281bd62ac200f1c8416682b

commit_message:
Vagrant: make provider network creation configurable

Currently the provider network is hard coded in few places. This
patch set will make it configurable in virtualbox.conf.yml. To
create a provider networ and its subnet, one needs to define few
new variables in virtualbox.conf.yml file like the following:

provider_network: "10.10.0.0/16”
provider_gateway: “10.10.0.1"
provider_start_ip: “10.10.0.101"
provider_end_ip: “10.10.255.250"

Change-Id: I64efb20cd8b0789fe556063ee67591c941c57b1a

commit_message:
WIP Cells: update block device mappings synchronously

Block device mapping update messages from a child cell to a parent cell
could either update or create a block device mapping.  Since there is no
unique constraint on the block_device_mapping table it is difficult to
prevent duplicate entries from being created when multiple messages are
sent in quick succession.

This aims to work around that by changing the interaction in two ways.
First this separates the update and create call so that an update
doesn't inadvertently create a bdm.  And the updates are done
synchronously so that multiple messages don't race with each other.

Change-Id: I5e77369d2ac68a868040853d9cdf0925d4990856

commit_message:
Make rescheduling of l3 agent more resilient

In order to make l3 agent restart more resilient
and idempotent do:

1) delete agent after resource is stopped and
all the stuff is cleaned up

2) reschedule not only dead routers/networks but also
orphaned routers/networks

3) enclose get_pid_list_for_ns_list function argument
in cleanup function into double quoutes
or it will use only the first argument
and will not work with several networks

Related-Bug: #1371550
Related-Bug: #1375817

Conflicts:
	deployment/puppet/neutron/files/ocf/neutron-agent-l3

Change-Id: I90338ff2df2703e121a6075ad1e60a442c88591f

Add two new options disabled by default to set the
kombu serializer and compression algorithm:
http://docs.celeryproject.org/projects/kombu/en/latest/reference/kombu.html#message-producer

During the spec discussion, it was apparent that drivers
were doing things differently (ZMQ and pickling for example).
There was concerns around the CPU vs message size tradeoff among

'}]
commit_message:
[kombu] Implement experimental message compression

Add two new options disabled by default to set the
kombu serializer and compression algorithm:
http://docs.celeryproject.org/projects/kombu/en/latest/reference/kombu.html#message-producer

During the spec discussion, it was apparent that drivers
were doing things differently (ZMQ and pickling for example).
There was concerns around the CPU vs message size tradeoff among
other things:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/247668/

So in this review, we leave the defaults as it was before, but
add EXPERIMENTAL options, to see how these holds up in
a large stress test and will help test these in the CI as well.

Change-Id: If240774657c2175874c45243db7854ba372982bd

commit_message:
pin tempest to keep setuping heat roles

A recent commit in Tempest [1] broke backward compatibility for Heat
testing.
stack_owner_role is not managed anymore by Tempest and it makes tests
fails.

This is a workaround until it's sorted out in Tempest.
Until this time, we pin Tempest to a previous commit so we can continue
to test scenario002.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/commit/aa461b746bac5144d99454ebdfece860e3fd7173
Related-Bug: #1543785

Change-Id: Ib19c25b6e4d9af808a3abab4d4ecbded2f33c034

commit_message:
Fixes terminal_width on Windows

Windows does not support fcntl and the changes introduced
by commit e7c3c622759d4e9af09947dfb8a7faf52edaad07
broke Windows support.

This patch adds Windows support by means of the appropriate
OS API.

Closes-Bug: #1543958
Change-Id: Icd251b340457e44b0560b8fbb131dd3cf13fcedd

commit_message:
iSCSI initiator refactoring using iscsidsc.dll

This patch adds a new iscsi initiator utils class,
leveraging iscsidsc.dll functions.

The advantages are:
* Same error output as iscsicli, without the proccess spawn
  overhead
* Improved overall performance, having finer control over
  the iSCSI initiator and avoiding unnecessary operations
* Fixed bugs related to LUN discovery
* Static targets are used instead of having portal discovery
  sessions. This will let us use backends that require
  discovery credentials (which may be different than the
  credentials used when logging in targets)
* improved MPIO support (the caller must request logging in the
  target for each of the available portals. Logging in multiple
  targets exporting the same LUN is also supported). Also, a
  specific initiator can be requested when creating sessions.

Closes-Bug: #1403836
Closes-Bug: #1372823
Closes-Bug: #1372827

Co-Authored-By: Alin Balutoiu <abalutoiu@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Change-Id: Ie037cf1712a28e85e5eca445eea3df883c6b6831

commit_message:
Add diskutils module

This patch adds a new module, used for disk related operations.

It adds a new method for retrieving disk unique id. We need this
method for os-brick, which returns the Unique id of the attached
volumes.

Note that for iSCSI/FC volumes, os-brick uses scsi_id to retrieve
the page 83 SCSI identifier, prepending the id type. We want to
remain consistent with the information provided by Linux os-brick
connectors so we'll do the same.

The method used for retrieving the disk number from a device name
has also been moved in this new module, previously residing in
vmutils as it will also be used by os-brick.

Also, the method used for rescanning disks has been moved here.

Change-Id: I0eac17c317a8d25da44b86feb58d6e8556f642eb

commit_message:
Fix fallocate test on newer util-linux

Newer util-linux raises an error when calling fallocate with the -n
option if the target file does not already exist. This is because the
-n option directs it to retain the file's existing size. A
non-existent file does not have an existing size. fallocate in older
releases of util-linux creates a zero-sized file in this case. This
results in _can_fallocate() always returning false, and therefore
never preallocating.

While this may reasonably be argued to be a regression in util-linux,
the -n option doesn't make sense here anyway, so we remove it.

Closes-Bug: #1543181

Change-Id: Ie96fa71e7d2641d30572b8eda5609dd3ca5b6708

commit_message:
Bug in Lambda smart-type was fixed

Lambda smart-type was handling its argument incorrectly
except for the case when it is an expression (which is the most
common case). Because of this it was impossible to provide
lambda arguments from outside using python lambdas or
constants

Change-Id: I52b5114c7764ce0fe0af25823948661c578181f1

commit_message:
Refactors base classes

Base classes should define interface between driver and
upper oslo messaging layer and shouldn't have fields and
methods used for internal driver's purposes.

1) base listener: + prefetch_size attribute;
                  -driver attribute
2) base incomingMessage: - reply method
                         - listener attribute
3) base RpcIncomingMessage added - it is incomingMessage + reply method

Change-Id: Ic2c0fce830763eb4e00f2cca789e9c1c6b5420ed

commit_message:
Add PushedDataSourceDriver class

PushedDataSourceDriver is a parent driver class for push type datasource
service. When updating table with pushed data, a subclass of the
PushedDataSourceDriver calls update_entire_data method with table_id and
object file for updating.

Partially implement blueprint: push-type-datasource-driver

Change-Id: Id979ae74fc8e28a9deb45909eeedc60d67e84d59

commit_message:
Emit instance life cycle events

The PowerVM REST API allows a handler to be registered for events
from PowerVM. From the events it can be determined if a VM has
had a state change.  This change set registers for those events
and determines if the state change is one that should trigger
an instance life cycle event to the compute manager. The compute
manager then can sync the power state between OpenStack and
PowerVM. Normally, _sync_power_states is only called via a
periodic task which defaults to 10 minute intervals.

Change-Id: I33363d4b9dfef3fafc9125dd283660417dbf3186

commit_message:
[Verify] Configure the 'auth_version' option

While registering a deployment in Rally we can specify different
auth URLs (V2 auth URL or V3 auth URL). For example:

http://172.16.49.231:5000/v3 or http://172.16.49.231:5000/v2.0

So we should consider such cases and depending on it we should
specify correct auth version in the tempest.conf file.

commit_message:
Add Wrapper classes for list, dict, tuple

Added wrapper classes which are inherited from base data types list,
tuple and dict. Each of these wrapper classes contains a 'request_ids'
attribute which will be populated with a 'x-openstack-request_id'
received in a header from a response body.

This change is required to return 'request_id' from
client to log request_id mappings of cross projects.

Partial-Implements: blueprint return-request-id-to-caller
Change-Id: I3aadb4d8bf675e20f2094b66a23ac20f455a99eb

[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-01-15 21:50:57.000000000', 'files': ['specs/mitaka/approved/image-import/import-request-example-sl.json', 'specs/mitaka/approved/image-import/import-schema.json', 'specs/mitaka/approved/image-import/import-request-example-gd.json', 'specs/mitaka/approved/image-import/image-import-refactor.rst'], 'message': "Remove `target_*` fields

A cloud must choose what the best target format for its own deployment

shouldn't worry about what the target formats in a cloud are. To some
extent, the user should not care about the image being converted at all.

This patch removes the requirement of passing `target_` fields in the

Glance already provides a way for cloud operators to specify what format

"}]
commit_message:
Remove `target_*` fields

A cloud must choose what the best target format for its own deployment
is without requiring the user to pass this information over. A user
shouldn't worry about what the target formats in a cloud are. To some
extent, the user should not care about the image being converted at all.

This patch removes the requirement of passing `target_` fields in the
import call but it keeps them, as a way to inform the user how the cloud
operates, in the `info` call.

Glance already provides a way for cloud operators to specify what format
images should be converted to: `conversion_format`

MitakaPriority
Change-Id: I60e2987e430a2f4a2e0dc3f34e96577a1c854364

commit_message:
Add forward slash for node path patch

Ironic cli allow to patch attributes w/o forward slash
at the beginning:
    ironic node-update <node_id> add 'driver_info/attr'='my_attr'
Inspector fails if driver info in rules provided in same manner,
this change add head forward slash to path if it's missing.

Closes-Bug: #1529809
Change-Id: I4423184e15d5779c59a903b50554db0550ba3d83

commit_message:
call() function was added

call() function allows to execute any other yaql
function or method by its name, args/kwargs and
receiver.

This is a compensation for lack of ability to expand lists/dicts
(*args and **kwargs) upon call.

Change-Id: Id0c5c597d158856e8c17ce40d4fa3423079a4c3d

commit_message:
Allow for eradicating Pure volumes on Cinder delete

This change adds in a config option which, when enabled, will cause
the Pure Storage volume drivers to eradicate volumes, snapshots, and
protection groups on delete for their Cinder counterpart.

With this config enabled an admin will NOT be able to recover data once
objects are deleted. By default the new config option is disabled and
volumes, snapshots, and protection group snapshots will be retained
pending eradication where they can be recovered for a period of time.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1537187

Change-Id: Ib3656bb64e5104f6bd05d28535cf91a46a038b55

commit_message:
Added Keystone and RequestID headers to CORS middleware

CORS middleware's latent configuration feature, new in 3.0.0,
allows adding headers that apply to all valid origins.
This patch adds headers commonly used in openstack to searchlight's paste
pipeline, so that operators do not have to be aware of additional
configuration magic to ensure that browsers can talk to the API.

For more information:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html#configuration-for-pastedeploy

Change-Id: I9b7e2436f882ec778ea6880d5982a28f5c1c8959

* Chain tests that value is of all of provided smart types (i.e. AND for smart types)
* NotOfType tests that value is not of provided smart type (i.e. NOT for smart type)

commit_message:
logging: don't override default logging_context_format_string value

oslo.log already defines default value for the option that contains all
the needed information (user name, project name, ...), so there is no
need to override it for neutron and nova.

The change will also add pid information to context-aware log messages
that was missing before and is included in oslo.log default format
string.

See: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.log/blob/master/oslo_log/_options.py#L98

Related-Bug: #1433687
Depends-On: I95e803b96e6e3e5b8c12298dc6327b974330c639

commit_message:
Detect arithmetic compound

As described in comments, ((expr)) has a trap that if expr is 0, the
return value is 1.  This will trigger a failure with "set -e" and can
be very confusing.  It is good defensive programming to avoid this
with explicit assignment.

Change-Id: Id57df3ff8127601429426c177a10e8eaec30c504

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-08-11 20:03:14.000000000', 'files': ['lib/cinder'], 'message': 'Bump up max_pool_size and max_overflow

A backup restore tempest test failed due to the lost connection to MySQL.
In Cinder volume log, we see the following error:
"Connection pool is full, discarding connection"

In Cinder backup log, we see the following error:
Exception during message handling: (pymysql.err.OperationalError) (2013,
'Lost connection to MySQL server during query')

This patch bumps up max_pool_size and max_overflow in cinder.conf to
allow more db connections. max_pool_size is the maximum number of SQL
connections to keep open in a pool. max_overflow is the maximum number
of overflow connections with sqlalchemy. By default, max_pool_size is 5
and max_overflow is 10. This patches bumps them up to 20 and 30 respectively:

max_pool_size=20
max_overflow=30

Change-Id: Ifef8dc15fb6d0a07ea52d469c5185619e69bdcbf
Partial-Bug: #1483434
'}]
commit_message:
Bump up max_pool_size and max_overflow

A backup restore tempest test failed due to the lost connection to MySQL.
In Cinder volume log, we see the following error:
"Connection pool is full, discarding connection"

In Cinder backup log, we see the following error:
Exception during message handling: (pymysql.err.OperationalError) (2013,
'Lost connection to MySQL server during query')

This patch bumps up max_pool_size and max_overflow in cinder.conf to
allow more db connections. max_pool_size is the maximum number of SQL
connections to keep open in a pool. max_overflow is the maximum number
of overflow connections with sqlalchemy. By default, max_pool_size is 5
and max_overflow is 10. This patches bumps them up to 20 and 30 respectively:

max_pool_size=20
max_overflow=30

Change-Id: Ifef8dc15fb6d0a07ea52d469c5185619e69bdcbf
Partial-Bug: #1483434

subject: Handle argument line-up in continuations
revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2016-02-09 04:09:58.000000000', 'files': ['bashate/tests/samples/E003_bad.sh', 'bashate/bashate.py', 'bashate/tests/samples/E003_good.sh', 'bashate/tests/test_bashate.py'], 'message': 'Handle argument line-up in continuations

Emacs in particluar does some indenting where it will try to align
continued lines up with the first argument, e.g.

  a_long_command arg1 \
                 arg2 arg3

Our current check will just barf on this when the offset isn't a
multiple of 4.  By passing "logical_line" to the offset checker, we
can find the first argument on the first line, and allow the whole
thing through if everything lines up.

Change-Id: I7f3369e4888353d2ba4ba2e48f3aaec4d1135b53
'}]
commit_message:
Handle argument line-up in continuations

Emacs in particluar does some indenting where it will try to align
continued lines up with the first argument, e.g.

  a_long_command arg1 \
                 arg2 arg3

Our current check will just barf on this when the offset isn't a
multiple of 4.  By passing "logical_line" to the offset checker, we
can find the first argument on the first line, and allow the whole
thing through if everything lines up.

Change-Id: I7f3369e4888353d2ba4ba2e48f3aaec4d1135b53

subject: Cleanup continuation line handling
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2016-02-09 04:00:05.000000000', 'files': ['bashate/bashate.py'], 'message': 'Cleanup continuation line handling

Rework things to collect continuation lines into "logical_lines".  We
convert this to an array (holding all lines of the continuation) for
simplicity.

For now, retain the status quo by running the existing checks over
each line as before.  However, this gives us the flexibility to do
different things for continuations, like allow different offsets.

Change-Id: I7bee246c9fd77ccdc4be3c2ba605d54d6fb81c86
'}]
commit_message:
Cleanup continuation line handling

Rework things to collect continuation lines into "logical_lines".  We
convert this to an array (holding all lines of the continuation) for
simplicity.

For now, retain the status quo by running the existing checks over
each line as before.  However, this gives us the flexibility to do
different things for continuations, like allow different offsets.

Change-Id: I7bee246c9fd77ccdc4be3c2ba605d54d6fb81c86

[{'number': 4, 'created': '2016-02-09 04:00:05.000000000', 'files': ['bashate/bashate.py', 'bashate/tests/samples/heredoc_ignore.sh', 'bashate/tests/test_bashate.py'], 'message': "Ignore heredoc contents

I noticed that we end up treating a heredoc as one big logical line,
then passing it through things like the line-length check.  So

cat <<EOF
this is normal lines
that get picked up as a long line!
EOF

end up triggering the long-line exception ... clearly not what is
intended.

In fact, there's not much we can do with heredocs.  They are usually
some weird syntax for a config file, or something else you're writing
out in bulk.  Often they have offsets that just don't match what we
want, etc.

Thus most logical thing to do seems to be to just ignore whatever is
in the heredoc.

I also noticed we don't handle <<'EOF', which is another common idiom,
so add that to the regex.  Also add a test-case to ensure we're
ignoring the heredoc contents.

Change-Id: I2e3d66f27ff4c0d1f542511ca3e19c29a596896f
"}]
commit_message:
Ignore heredoc contents

I noticed that we end up treating a heredoc as one big logical line,
then passing it through things like the line-length check.  So

cat <<EOF
this is normal lines
that get picked up as a long line!
EOF

end up triggering the long-line exception ... clearly not what is
intended.

In fact, there's not much we can do with heredocs.  They are usually
some weird syntax for a config file, or something else you're writing
out in bulk.  Often they have offsets that just don't match what we
want, etc.

Thus most logical thing to do seems to be to just ignore whatever is
in the heredoc.

I also noticed we don't handle <<'EOF', which is another common idiom,
so add that to the regex.  Also add a test-case to ensure we're
ignoring the heredoc contents.

Change-Id: I2e3d66f27ff4c0d1f542511ca3e19c29a596896f

subject: Replace heredoc fail-to-end detection E012 with "bash -n"
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2016-02-09 04:00:05.000000000', 'files': ['bashate/tests/samples/E012_bad.sh', 'bashate/bashate.py', 'bashate/tests/test_bashate.py', 'bashate/messages.py'], 'message': 'Replace heredoc fail-to-end detection E012 with "bash -n"

Currently E012 (detect if heredoc doesn't end) basically doesn't work;
it relies on having multiple files specified to check.  The logic is
currently that if a heredoc is open and we start a new-file, we missed
it.

As we even say in the comments, bash will warn about this.  Luckily,
"bash -n" does pop out this warning when we forget to close a
heredoc.

So modify the existing bash syntax check to catch this too.  Because
it's a warning, bash doesn't exit with !0, so rework things to just
parse output in all cases.  I also found a bit of inconsistency with
output, as described in the comments.

Remove the existing check, and add a testcase.

Change-Id: I292a926d3297a283f74f7d47b7c7aa3c42c9f030
'}]
commit_message:
Replace heredoc fail-to-end detection E012 with "bash -n"

Currently E012 (detect if heredoc doesn't end) basically doesn't work;
it relies on having multiple files specified to check.  The logic is
currently that if a heredoc is open and we start a new-file, we missed
it.

As we even say in the comments, bash will warn about this.  Luckily,
"bash -n" does pop out this warning when we forget to close a
heredoc.

So modify the existing bash syntax check to catch this too.  Because
it's a warning, bash doesn't exit with !0, so rework things to just
parse output in all cases.  I also found a bit of inconsistency with
output, as described in the comments.

Remove the existing check, and add a testcase.

Change-Id: I292a926d3297a283f74f7d47b7c7aa3c42c9f030

subject: Use round robin failover strategy for Kombu driver
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1669, 'name': 'Julien Danjou', 'display_name': 'jd', 'email': 'julien@danjou.info', 'username': 'jdanjou'}, {'_account_id': 2813, 'name': 'Mehdi Abaakouk', 'email': 'sileht@sileht.net', 'username': 'sileht'}, {'_account_id': 5638, 'name': 'Davanum Srinivas', 'email': 'davanum@gmail.com', 'username': 'dims-v'}, {'_account_id': 7109, 'name': 'Dmitry Mescheryakov (dmitryme)', 'email': 'dmescheryakov@mirantis.com', 'username': 'dmitryme'}, {'_account_id': 9796, 'name': 'ChangBo Guo', 'email': 'glongwave@gmail.com', 'username': 'gcb'}, {'_account_id': 13290, 'name': 'Oleksii Zamiatin', 'email': 'ozamiatin@mirantis.com', 'username': 'ozamiatin'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 4, 'created': '2015-11-30 11:09:01.000000000', 'files': ['oslo_messaging/tests/drivers/test_impl_rabbit.py', 'oslo_messaging/_drivers/impl_rabbit.py'], 'message': "Use round robin failover strategy for Kombu driver

Shuffle strategy we use right now leads to increased reconnection time
and provides no benefit. Sometimes it might lead to RPC operations
timeout because the strategy provides no guarantee on how long the
reconnection process will take. See the referenced bug for details.

On the other side, round-robin strategy provides least achievable
reconnection time. It also provides guarantee that if K of N RabbitMQ
hosts are alive, it will take at most N - K + 1 attempts to
successfully reconnect to RabbitMQ cluster.

With shuffle strategy during failover clients connect to random hosts
and so the load is distributed evenly between alive RabbitMQs.
But since we shuffle list of hosts before providing it to Kombu, load
will be distributed evenly with round-robin strategy as well.

DocImpact
A new configuration option kombu_failover_strategy for Kombu driver is
added. It determines how the next RabbitMQ node is chosen in case the
one we are currently connected to becomes unavailable. It takes effect
only if more than one RabbitMQ node is provided in config. Available
options are:

 * round-robin: each RabbitMQ host in the list is tried in cycle until
   oslo.messaging successfully connects. Since oslo.messaging
   shuffles list of RabbitMQ hosts, the order of hosts in the cycle
   will be random and will not depend on order provided in config.

 * shuffle: oslo.messaging selects a random host from the list and
   tries to connect to it. If connection fails, oslo.messaging repeats
   attempt to connect to another random host. Oslo.messaging stops
   once it successfully connects to a host. Note that in each
   iteration a host to connect is selected independently of previous
   iterations, i.e. it might happen that oslo.messaging will try to
   connect to the same host several times in a row.

The option's default value is round-robin. Before the option was
introduced, the default strategy was shuffle. For the reasoning,
see the main body of the commit message and the referenced bug.

Closes-Bug: #1519851
Change-Id: I9a510c86bd5a6ce8b707734385af1a83de82804e
"}]
commit_message:
Use round robin failover strategy for Kombu driver

Shuffle strategy we use right now leads to increased reconnection time
and provides no benefit. Sometimes it might lead to RPC operations
timeout because the strategy provides no guarantee on how long the
reconnection process will take. See the referenced bug for details.

On the other side, round-robin strategy provides least achievable
reconnection time. It also provides guarantee that if K of N RabbitMQ
hosts are alive, it will take at most N - K + 1 attempts to
successfully reconnect to RabbitMQ cluster.

With shuffle strategy during failover clients connect to random hosts
and so the load is distributed evenly between alive RabbitMQs.
But since we shuffle list of hosts before providing it to Kombu, load
will be distributed evenly with round-robin strategy as well.

DocImpact
A new configuration option kombu_failover_strategy for Kombu driver is
added. It determines how the next RabbitMQ node is chosen in case the
one we are currently connected to becomes unavailable. It takes effect
only if more than one RabbitMQ node is provided in config. Available
options are:

 * round-robin: each RabbitMQ host in the list is tried in cycle until
   oslo.messaging successfully connects. Since oslo.messaging
   shuffles list of RabbitMQ hosts, the order of hosts in the cycle
   will be random and will not depend on order provided in config.

 * shuffle: oslo.messaging selects a random host from the list and
   tries to connect to it. If connection fails, oslo.messaging repeats
   attempt to connect to another random host. Oslo.messaging stops
   once it successfully connects to a host. Note that in each
   iteration a host to connect is selected independently of previous
   iterations, i.e. it might happen that oslo.messaging will try to
   connect to the same host several times in a row.

The option's default value is round-robin. Before the option was
introduced, the default strategy was shuffle. For the reasoning,
see the main body of the commit message and the referenced bug.

Closes-Bug: #1519851
Change-Id: I9a510c86bd5a6ce8b707734385af1a83de82804e

has the plural names to match the change in the plugins repo.

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-01-28 17:06:02.000000000', 'files': ['heat/engine/resource.py'], 'message': "Prevent phantom user hooks

Clear an active user hook when an exit exception occurs (e.g. the thread is
cancelled). Previously we only caught Exception so exit exceptions were
excluded.

To also cover the case of an unclean exit (e.g. kill -9), don't wait on a
hook that is left over from some previous stack operation - only start the
hook if it is set in the current environment.

Change-Id: Ie894f416a898edeca3b6a123392853213893ff74
Closes-Bug: #1538733
(cherry picked from commit cee2aa07625be2bdacf0cd6abce65a5f641b4a13)
"}]
commit_message:
Prevent phantom user hooks

Clear an active user hook when an exit exception occurs (e.g. the thread is
cancelled). Previously we only caught Exception so exit exceptions were
excluded.

To also cover the case of an unclean exit (e.g. kill -9), don't wait on a
hook that is left over from some previous stack operation - only start the
hook if it is set in the current environment.

Change-Id: Ie894f416a898edeca3b6a123392853213893ff74
Closes-Bug: #1538733
(cherry picked from commit cee2aa07625be2bdacf0cd6abce65a5f641b4a13)

commit_message:
Update deb-mirror to download ubuntu docker image

This change updates the deb-mirror script download the ubuntu docker
image from mirror.fuel-infra.org because the version of docker provided
by Fuel 7.0 is no longer able to pull it down from the docker hub.

Change-Id: I5f7d95f4288520db4dc49557540ff1e8b569c2bb

commit_message:
Fix getting agent id in linuxbridge agent

If bridge_mappings is configured in linuxbridge agent, it will now
determine agent_id which is based on MAC address of first device
from bridge_mappings in correct way.

Change-Id: I940379b2fd3b5f8c96cdf3b7a3c0da78532491f6
Closes-bug: #1542923

commit_message:
Added *-npm-publish-draft job

This job performs the same work as the js-draft series,
with the added benefit that it does not require knowledge
of the underlying project hierarchy, nor custom hooks into
grunt to generate a release package. It calls the NPM lifecycle
'pack' event, which generates a release tarball. This tarball is
then extracted, and the contents of the configured directory
are then uploaded to docs-draft. A success pattern has been
included, so a passing build will link to the newly constructed
application directly.

Change-Id: I24c55738025284d9e0baef13ec8a9b49a90d4ef7

commit_message:
Prevent phantom user hooks

Clear an active user hook when an exit exception occurs (e.g. the thread is
cancelled). Previously we only caught Exception so exit exceptions were
excluded.

To also cover the case of an unclean exit (e.g. kill -9), don't wait on a
hook that is left over from some previous stack operation - only start the
hook if it is set in the current environment.

Change-Id: Ie894f416a898edeca3b6a123392853213893ff74
Closes-Bug: #1538733
(cherry picked from commit cee2aa07625be2bdacf0cd6abce65a5f641b4a13)

Apparently, fuel-agent doesn't handle any signal received except for SIGINT
which is automatically converted by python to KeyboardInterrupt() exception.

fuel-agent is unable to send signal for spawned processes, just because
utils.execute doesn't know PIDs of opened subprocessess. To mitigate that flaw,
fuel-agent will use process group to distribute signals.

A signal directed to a process group is delivered individually to all of the
processes that are members of the group.

commit_message:
Handle SIGTERM to shut down gracefully

Apparently, fuel-agent doesn't handle any signal received except for SIGINT
which is automatically converted by python to KeyboardInterrupt() exception.

fuel-agent is unable to send signal for spawned processes, just because
utils.execute doesn't know PIDs of opened subprocessess. To mitigate that flaw,
fuel-agent will use process group to distribute signals.

Process groups are used to control the distribution of signals.
A signal directed to a process group is delivered individually to all of the
processes that are members of the group.

That allows fuel-agent to send signals to subprocesses without knowing thier
exact PIDs.

Change-Id: Ie59c0425f031fa94e517b79df0a0fc3d0c3e7a07
Related-Bug: #1538645

commit_message:
Zfssaiscsi driver should return target_lun as int

The zfssaiscsi driver in initialize_connection()
returns iscsi_properties['target_lun'] as a string.
Solaris version of openstack expects it to be an int
and fails for the driver. Also other drivers report
it as an int. So this will make the zfssaiscsi driver
more consistent with other drivers.

Change-Id: Ifdbca7a02e2d797af9149cd185c2fa5dce661f66
Closes-bug: #1538582

commit_message:
Added CORS support to Barbican

This adds the CORS support middleware to Barbican, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly. Included
are Barbican's custom headers, so that anyone activating this
middleware does not have to explicitly enable them.

The paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by other middleware.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

Change-Id: If144ec774c01e8fc9e10903076fad11a0b946b6d

commit_message:
Update puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm gate to use zuul-clone

The main reason for this, we want to add a puppet-keystone gate job to
puppet-openstack-integration.  Doing this, requires us to use zuul to
clone the repo, and not using the local workspace from jenkins.

To make this work, we needed to create a new organization variable,
since we share this job between openstack, openstack-infra and
stackforge.

Change-Id: I41d92e6801337d7b39178e83ff349a8e8b8f574f
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

the boolean, otherwise we fail when we try to concatenate

TypeError: sequence item 6: expected string, bool found

commit_message:
Add the missing Client-ID check in wsgi v2

From wsgi v1.1 every request needs Client-ID. But the check is
missing in v2. This patch fixes it.

APIimpact

Closes-bug: #1540699
Co-Authored-By: wangxiyuan <wangxiyuan@huawei.com>
Co-Authored-By: Eva Balycheva <ubershy@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Docs: Removing manual target host steps that are automated

The packages I removed and kernel module load I removed are
both handled by the openstack-ansible-openstack_hosts role.

Therefore, we do not need to ask users to perform these steps
as they will be performed by OSA.

commit_message:
Fix wrong exception return in fixed_ips v2 extention

Currently, fixed_ips api raises HTTPNotFound if passing an invalid
ip address in url, I think this is not correct. It's better to return
HTTPBadRequest to end user when the api excepts a FixedIpInvalid
exception.

This patch fixes it and also the test cases.

Change-Id: I7b18b76745f9092456d511ad023a9ed3a24cca84

commit_message:
Limit max length of gen_random_resource_name

For example flavor name couldn't be longer than 25 chars (in Horizon).
This patch take last 'maxlen' characters of string, because there is
randomly generated part of whole string.

Closes-Bug: 1461118
Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing
Change-Id: I9098191a3faa0d255046c4023fced84c4ee2a814

commit_message:
Simplify checking for stack complete

This is a small simplification over Change-Id:
Id325e793a510e751ec4736883f6f97cb80a5623f
that should also not print out duplicated event lists.

This fixes the issue where the last event is seen, but the overcloud
stack is not yet CREATE_COMPLETE, which caused an infinte loop in the
client.

Change-Id: Idb5b02435667d6ed504e60a4ef6779ee4191c726
(cherry picked from commit cce455ab1afed0256ffe5b537517bcfb66240395)

Change of PLUMgrid plugin package and addition of new parameters.

The neutron-plugin-plumgrid package has been deprecated and new package
named networking-plumgrid is now used to provide the same services.
There are some new paramters added to support some new features.

Doc-ref: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PLUMgrid-Neutron

This change needs to be cherry-picked to stable/liberty as well.

commit_message:
Allow an attached volume to be extended

The purpose of this is spec to change the behavior of volume extend
API to allow an attached volume to be extended. This allows allow the
volume driver to extend the existing volume without first requiring
that the volume be detached and put back in the available state

Change-Id: I6188afb5dac4f56567c3b0b24c7b8eb56b413b30
blueprint: extend-attached-volume

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-02-09 16:23:08.000000000', 'files': ['tripleoclient/tests/test_utils.py', 'tripleoclient/utils.py', 'tripleoclient/exceptions.py', 'tripleoclient/v1/overcloud_deploy.py'], 'message': "Don't regenerate the overcloud passwords if the Heat stack exists

If the user is in the incorrect directory (one different from
where they originally deployed), the function to generate
passwords will create a new password file with random passwords.
This will then be sent to Heat and it will attempt to reconfigure
the passwords for all services (which currently isn't fully

commit_message:
Don't regenerate the overcloud passwords if the Heat stack exists

If the user is in the incorrect directory (one different from
where they originally deployed), the function to generate
passwords will create a new password file with random passwords.
This will then be sent to Heat and it will attempt to reconfigure
the passwords for all services (which currently isn't fully
supported and can leave users with a non-functioning overcloud).
The issue can be replicated with:

    openstack overcloud deploy --templates
    cd /tmp (or any other different directory)
    openstack overcloud deploy --templates

This changes the behaviour to display an error if the password
file can't be found, but the Heat stack already exists.

Closes-Bug: #1541342
Change-Id: I2ce63c254c10d6382d626b2f5436019971a26952

commit_message:
Handle missing plugin in is_service_available

When a client is not installed, Heat should behave as if the service was
unavailable. We recently started exposing exceptions when checking for
service availability, which displayed that it fails if the client plugin
returs None. Let's test and handle that case.

Change-Id: I71d5fd5be2efd7734d8569e4d26ab1b512453343
Closes-Bug: #1543759

commit_message:
Makes the iSCSI initiator name unique for compute nodes

When we utilise images for deployment, the iSCSI initiator name
is not unique, leading to problems with live migration. This
patch simply updates the iSCSI initiator name to a unique ID
randomly generated by iscsi-iname.

https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1244328

Change-Id: I170e7f45f67fa8ce70436f24807d1ed7808f2c32

subject: Fix failing tests in defcore test set
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-01-30 13:28:31.000000000', 'files': ['playbooks/roles/os_tempest/templates/tempest.conf.j2', 'playbooks/roles/os_tempest/defaults/main.yml'], 'message': "Fix failing tests in defcore test set

Currently, running the defcore test set fails on a couple of tests due
to incorrect tempest.conf configuration.  This commit does the
following to address:

1. Creates new tempest_network_tenant_network_cidr and
   tempest_network_tenant_network_mask_bits role defaults

In tempest.conf, tenant_network_cidr expects to be a bigger network
which it can create smaller subnets from using
tenant_network_mask_bits.  We currently set tenant_network_cidr to
'192.168.74.0/24' with a tenant_network_mask_bits of '24', which
obviously won't work.  The var tempest_network_tenant_network_cidr now
defaults to '192.168.74.0/24'
and tempest_network_tenant_network_mask_bits defaulting to '28'.  The
actual tenant network (tempest_private_subnet_cidr) that we create is
now '192.168.74.0/28', which fits into tenant_network_cidr.

2. Creates new tempest_compute_ssh_user role default

Some tests were failing as they were attempting to ssh to booted
instances using username 'root', which was confusing as we already set
image_ssh_user to 'cirros'.  Oddly, it was attempting to use the
tempest config ssh_user so setting that to cirros also ensures those
tests pass.

Change-Id: Ib6396d765bc974675ed3841a1f22cb75ea8fce5a
(cherry picked from commit f16bb31008ac6bd59d3deab67aa5d5e7c424dacd)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix failing tests in defcore test set

Currently, running the defcore test set fails on a couple of tests due
to incorrect tempest.conf configuration.  This commit does the
following to address:

1. Creates new tempest_network_tenant_network_cidr and
   tempest_network_tenant_network_mask_bits role defaults

In tempest.conf, tenant_network_cidr expects to be a bigger network
which it can create smaller subnets from using
tenant_network_mask_bits.  We currently set tenant_network_cidr to
'192.168.74.0/24' with a tenant_network_mask_bits of '24', which
obviously won't work.  The var tempest_network_tenant_network_cidr now
defaults to '192.168.74.0/24'
and tempest_network_tenant_network_mask_bits defaulting to '28'.  The
actual tenant network (tempest_private_subnet_cidr) that we create is
now '192.168.74.0/28', which fits into tenant_network_cidr.

2. Creates new tempest_compute_ssh_user role default

Some tests were failing as they were attempting to ssh to booted
instances using username 'root', which was confusing as we already set
image_ssh_user to 'cirros'.  Oddly, it was attempting to use the
tempest config ssh_user so setting that to cirros also ensures those
tests pass.

Change-Id: Ib6396d765bc974675ed3841a1f22cb75ea8fce5a
(cherry picked from commit f16bb31008ac6bd59d3deab67aa5d5e7c424dacd)

subject: Check and monitoring tool for repo consistency
revisions:
[{'number': 7, 'created': '2016-02-02 08:28:39.000000000', 'files': ['repo-monitor/check-package-functions.sh', 'repo-monitor/check-deb-package.sh', 'repo-monitor/properties.sh', 'repo-monitor/check-rpm-package.sh'], 'message': 'Check and monitoring tool for repo consistency

In current workflow for every MOS project in review.fuel-infra.org we
first merge the patch to the source repository and then trigger the
job which publishes packages to the packages repository (deb- and rpm-
repos).
There are many circumstances which can cause publishing failures:
network issues, hardware problems, software misconfiguration, etc. So
this tool verify the content of the package repository is aligned with
the code merged in Gerrit.

Change-Id: I1ed0768b2e9261260c3b164e117cd057ae3dc817
'}]
commit_message:
Check and monitoring tool for repo consistency

In current workflow for every MOS project in review.fuel-infra.org we
first merge the patch to the source repository and then trigger the
job which publishes packages to the packages repository (deb- and rpm-
repos).
There are many circumstances which can cause publishing failures:
network issues, hardware problems, software misconfiguration, etc. So
this tool verify the content of the package repository is aligned with
the code merged in Gerrit.

Change-Id: I1ed0768b2e9261260c3b164e117cd057ae3dc817

commit_message:
move our API 2.0 compat jobs to experimental

These jobs were important during the initial transition to demonstrate
we were not regressing, but in tree testing has demonstrated just as
effective. Put these into the experimental queue so we can run them on
demand, but don't take up check resources for them.

Change-Id: Ie4bd68d4469776a944cfddbb5ab6fe9204f705bc

commit_message:
Remove and deprecate conductor provider_fw_rule_get_all()

This is unused and can be cleaned out. The manager method is left for
backwards compatibility but changed to return an empty list since that
yields the same result as before. The db query always resulted in no
rows being returned since the table contained nothing.

Change-Id: Id5f0406c64f9a6ef9e4220cd6e6d2facbf40a550

nova which could be out of date, so any floating ips
added wont show up unless you refresh the whole page.

commit_message:
Simplify checking for stack complete

This is a small simplification over Change-Id:
Id325e793a510e751ec4736883f6f97cb80a5623f
that should also not print out duplicated event lists.

This fixes the issue where the last event is seen, but the overcloud
stack is not yet CREATE_COMPLETE, which caused an infinte loop in the
client.

subject: Replace eventlet-based raw socket client with requests
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-02-09 22:08:05.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/unit/test_wsgi.py'], 'message': "Replace eventlet-based raw socket client with requests

There's no discernable reason why we need to use a raw
eventlet-based client TestWSGIServerWithSSL to confirm that a
wsgi server is listening correctly and returning the expected
response, especially since using eventlet leads to unreliable
i/o on the socket unless there is an explicit yield before
asserting the value of the response.

So requests is used to query the servers and verify the response.

Change-Id: I00c1c1e93eb7c66c3370434db4e3e6c00087f8aa
Closes-Bug: #1543766
(cherry picked from commit d754a830861fb55b047e7b4d43ba7f485fc120dd)
(cherry picked from commit 0d5b3c6d7a4463ba6972507d38300f70cbf87c16)
"}]
commit_message:
Replace eventlet-based raw socket client with requests

There's no discernable reason why we need to use a raw
eventlet-based client TestWSGIServerWithSSL to confirm that a
wsgi server is listening correctly and returning the expected
response, especially since using eventlet leads to unreliable
i/o on the socket unless there is an explicit yield before
asserting the value of the response.

So requests is used to query the servers and verify the response.

Change-Id: I00c1c1e93eb7c66c3370434db4e3e6c00087f8aa
Closes-Bug: #1543766
(cherry picked from commit d754a830861fb55b047e7b4d43ba7f485fc120dd)
(cherry picked from commit 0d5b3c6d7a4463ba6972507d38300f70cbf87c16)

commit_message:
Handle client exceptions in list_resource_types

We've recently changed to expose exceptions when checking for
service availability.

However, when listing resource types, we also check for
service availability, where the exception is uncaught.
We can ignore any client exceptions and exclude the
resource_type from the list.

Change-Id: I8d8c65e46f417600e9cb929148e43c09ac315758
Partial-Bug: #1543759

commit_message:
Fix fuel-agent crashes during ks_spaces validation

fuel-agent validates pm_data.ks_spaces data structure to have a valid
schema, to be non-empty and to have a root partition less than 16T.

If it encounters a volume which does not have an assigned mountpoint
(could be an LVM PV) and at the same time is larger than 16T, it crashes
with a KeyError.

This change avoids a crash by using dict.get which does not throw an
exception in case a key is not present in the dict.

Change-Id: I34971f756d6b17c334dd5f7834af5ca778f2462a
Closes-Bug: 1526845
(cherry picked from commit 96a19bd7911a7c535078284acfe355b850fd4f24)

queries module had its own NO_VALUE constant

Because yaql runtime doesn't know anything about this

commit_message:
Wrong parameter default for first()/last() was fixed

queries module had its own NO_VALUE constant
that was used for specification of default value for
first() and last() method arguments.

Because yaql runtime doesn't know anything about this
value it assumed that the parameter must be of its default
value type (type(DEFAULT_VALUE)) or null. Because NO_VALUE
is not accessible from YAQL expressions the only possible
default was null value. Or other parameter values caused
an exception.

Change-Id: I9518611fa02ec6eb5f43014182750c4c1ddff072
Closes-Bug: #1543873

commit_message:
Wrong parameter default for first()/last() was fixed

queries module had its own NO_VALUE constant
that was used for specification of default value for
first() and last() method arguments.

Because yaql runtime doesn't know anything about this
value it assumed that the parameter must be of its default
value type (type(DEFAULT_VALUE)) or null. Because NO_VALUE
is not accessible from YAQL expressions the only possible
default was null value. Or other parameter values caused
an exception.

Change-Id: I9518611fa02ec6eb5f43014182750c4c1ddff072
Closes-Bug: #1543873

The code was doing:

  if not is_shared_instance_path:
      ...
  if not (is_block_migration or is_shared_instance_path):
      ...

Apply De Morgan's law to the second if block makes this cleanup
obvious:

  if not is_block_migration and not is_shared_instance_path:

Change-Id: I54d599d29c9050faa45c686a9522f4c1cde938f9

commit_message:
Trivial logic cleanup in libvirt pre_live_migration

The code was doing:

  if not is_shared_instance_path:
      ...
  if not (is_block_migration or is_shared_instance_path):
      ...

Apply De Morgan's law to the second if block makes this cleanup
obvious:

  if not is_block_migration and not is_shared_instance_path:
      ...

This trivial cleanup improves readability.

Change-Id: I54d599d29c9050faa45c686a9522f4c1cde938f9

revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2015-08-07 20:49:34.000000000', 'files': ['keystone/models/token_model.py', 'keystone/tests/unit/token/test_token_model.py'], 'message': 'Changing UnexpectedError exception to Unauthorized exception

When the token is dual scoped, UnexpectedError exception is raised,
this exception is not caught in most of the place when KeystoneToken
is instantiated, thus, seen from the client, http status code 500 is
returned with the message title as "Internal Server Error".

This is not precisely correct, since this is authentication credentials
related exception, Unauthorized exception with the http status code
401 is better in this case. Rather than capture this exception and raise
Unauthorized exception again (as what it is when the exception is TokenNotFound)
we can just change the exception as Unauthorized exception in the class of
KeystoneToken.

Change-Id: I457576b23ab52d08bab2ce006d5c7a684575d7e9
'}]
commit_message:
Changing UnexpectedError exception to Unauthorized exception

When the token is dual scoped, UnexpectedError exception is raised,
this exception is not caught in most of the place when KeystoneToken
is instantiated, thus, seen from the client, http status code 500 is
returned with the message title as "Internal Server Error".

This is not precisely correct, since this is authentication credentials
related exception, Unauthorized exception with the http status code
401 is better in this case. Rather than capture this exception and raise
Unauthorized exception again (as what it is when the exception is TokenNotFound)
we can just change the exception as Unauthorized exception in the class of
KeystoneToken.

commit_message:
Getting local files creates symlinks instead of copying

Dumping shotgun resources is now done through symlinks. All local
resources are symlinked in dump directory, after that dump is compressed
with tar using -h option (--dereference).

Excluding files from tarball is now done by passing --exclude option to
tar instead of removing files before taring to avoid deleting logs.

Symlinks are created by 'ln -s' command because of wildcards used in
shotgun settings.

Change-Id: Ie9a0ab51d5874cd46a3919179def0aef407e7340
Partial-bug: 1529182

commit_message:
Move mongodb_replset setup to step 2

The HA setup was failing because, if mongodb::server::replset is set,
then the replset_members or replset_config parameters must also be
specified. So this change ensures that the replset_members are set both
in the server resource (which will just set up the configuration) and in
the actual replset resource.

Change-Id: I537053a1526531a82da0deabf7caac3e73bd5ffa

commit_message:
On Windows and OSX, the 'socket' python module does not contain the
attributes TCP_KEEPCNT or TCP_KEEPINTVL, causing services
consuming the library to malfunction.

Adds conditionals for adding the mentioned socket attributes
to the socket options.

Change-Id: I7370e03d8bc5ef3e06c97f18b79a90069ee5b3ea
Closes-Bug: #1527131

commit_message:
Rename plugins folders to standard Ansible names

The standard Ansible names for the plugins folders [1] are singular.

This patch renames our plural names to singular names so that when
the plugins are downloaded into a default location there is no further
configuration required.

[1] https://github.com/ansible/ansible/blob/devel/lib/ansible/constants.py

Change-Id: Ib965750f267d11287a6196e2544c3a014a3e2029

subject: Revert "Convert project to os-testr"
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-02-09 17:22:57.000000000', 'files': ['test-requirements.txt', 'tox.ini'], 'message': 'Revert "Convert project to os-testr"

os-testr is much less usable than testr overall in my experience.
os-testr does not bring enough to the table based upon how much it
takes away. The differences and difficulties in running only
failing tests, and generally different workflow from keystone
proper swings the choice towards testr. The regex option and
slight (strictly preference) readability changes does not
make a big enough impact to keep os-testr in keystoneauth.

This reverts commit ec16789cf11717e3d04cf1beb0e27f22cc98f156.

Change-Id: I241cba452f65522e0137fc0d023ca180ecf75941
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Convert project to os-testr"

os-testr is much less usable than testr overall in my experience.
os-testr does not bring enough to the table based upon how much it
takes away. The differences and difficulties in running only
failing tests, and generally different workflow from keystone
proper swings the choice towards testr. The regex option and
slight (strictly preference) readability changes does not
make a big enough impact to keep os-testr in keystoneauth.

This reverts commit ec16789cf11717e3d04cf1beb0e27f22cc98f156.

Change-Id: I241cba452f65522e0137fc0d023ca180ecf75941

commit_message:
Move v3->v2 compat static methods

Move the v3->v2 compat static methods into their own module. This
is done to help reduce interdependencies between the keystone
common controller and wsgi modules. This is in preperation
of moving the required middleware objects into the main

commit_message:
libvirt: Race condition leads to instance in error

ImageCacheManager deletes base image while image backend is copying
image to the instance path leading instance to go in the error state.

Acquired lock before removing image from cache. If libvirt is copying
image to the instance path, image cache manager won't be able to remove
it until libvirt finishes copying image completely.

Closes-Bug: 1256838
Closes-Bug: 1470437
Co-Authored-By: Michael Still <mikal@stillhq.com>
Depends-On: I337ce28e2fc516c91bec61ca3639ebff0029ad49
Change-Id: I376cc951922c338669fdf3f83da83e0d3cea1532

commit_message:
Quota API is now compatible with keystone API v2

Before, the quota API used to fail to perform calls with specified
keystone API v2, because the keystone client used in code was set
to v3 and all quota operations used to assume that the user would
use only keystone API v3.
Now, we use the generic client, which discovers the version of the
keystone API, so depending on that, the quota API can perform
appropriate operations.

Change-Id: I32595a37a9fe74ede77c92f76e0865f4c9371f65
Closes-Bug: 1517043
(cherry picked from commit ffd32c7e1947189eee701c417d9f72982f720a11)

commit_message:
Fix DisplayCommandBase comments for cliff ShowOne subclass tests

As bug #1477199 describes, the wrong comment below is all over the
unit test code of OSC.

    # DisplayCommandBase.take_action() returns two tuples

There is no such class named DisplayCommandBase in OSC. It is in cliff.

All OSC command classes inherit from the base classes in cliff,
class Command, class Lister and class ShowOne. It is like this:

Object
|--> Command
     |--> DisplayCommandBase
          |--> Lister
          |--> ShowOne

take_action() is an abstract method of class Command, and generally is
overwritten by subclasses.
* Command.take_action() returns nothing.
* Lister.take_action() returns a tuple which contains a tuple of columns
  and a generator used to generate the data.
* ShowOne.take_action() returns an iterator which contains a tuple of
  columns and a tuple of data.

So, this problem should be fixed in 3 steps:
1. Remove all DisplayCommandBase comments for tests of classes inheriting
   from class Command in cliff as it returns nothing.
2. Fix all DisplayCommandBase comments for tests of classes inheriting
   from class Lister in cliff. Lister.take_action() returns a tuple and
   a generator.
3. Fix all DisplayCommandBase comments for tests of classes inheriting
   from class ShowOne in cliff. ShowOne.take_action() returns two tuples.

This patch finishes step 3 in all but identity tests. There are too many
such comments in identity tests. So fix them all in another patch.

Change-Id: I1afe4852069d25d562a9448ec2bf2cff58955052
Partial-bug: #1477199

commit_message:
Ensure ceilometer-polling is installed for vmware_compute

Since the vmware_compute install process is quite different
from typical compute node deployment, this package gets missed
during deploy time. The ceilometer-polling package needs to be
called in compute_vmware.pp manifests.

Change-Id: If84e1cc388e3adda54ae63bdb4901e013ea14e3f
Closes-Bug: #1537403
(cherry picked from commit 2e19f9ce27f511575b3f56a57cc31dc843bc83c2)

commit_message:
Support workflow id in execution operations

Workflow UUID will be used in Mistral instead of workflow name, which is
not unique in the system. So, we need to support using workflow UUID in
execution operations.

Partially implements: blueprint use-workflow-id-in-rest-api
Change-Id: I1b83eb75aa89484235e2150ab4f111da4ea766b7

commit_message:
Only match #!/bin/bash in scripts

Our dib-lint checking is only considering scripts with #!/bin/bash.
While there's nothing really wrong with some other shebang line like
"#!/usr/bin/env bash" let's keep things consistent.

We can use the same regex match to reduce a few forks in the main
checking.

Also a minor cleanup to the file matching

Change-Id: I609721b2671e704ea26075dad7e5b39a8b858f6b

subject: Re-deploy the Ceilometer venv if it mismatches the repo
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-01-29 02:04:43.000000000', 'files': ['playbooks/roles/os_ceilometer/defaults/main.yml', 'playbooks/roles/os_ceilometer/tasks/ceilometer_install.yml'], 'message': 'Re-deploy the Ceilometer venv if it mismatches the repo

We currently have two issues with venvs:

- if you update your venv on the repo server, it is not possible for
  that updated venv to land on the service's container as the get_url
  task always skips if the file exists (even if the file is different)
- if you have an updated venv on the repo server and forcefully delete
  the cached venv tarball on the service's container, the new tarball
  will get unarchived over top of the existing venv

This commit does the following:

- gets the checksum of the /var/cache tarball and downloads checksum
  file from repo server
- updates "Attempt venv download" to only download the venv if the
  cache doesn't exist or if the local and remote checksums differ
- adds a "force: true" to "Attempt venv download" task so that the venv
  tarball will get re-downloaded when the when condition is true (this
  is necessary otherwise the download will get skipped since the
  destination already exists)
- adds a new task "Remove existing venv" so we can first remove the
  venv before we unarchive the potentially new venv from the repo
  server
- updates "Create ceilometer venv dir" and "Unarchive pre-built venv"
  tasks to only proceed if "ceilometer_get_venv | changed", which
  prevents these tasks from running when they the venv tarball hasn't
  changed
- adds multiple service restarts to
  os_ceilometer/tasks/ceilometer_install.yml so that ceilometer will
  restart correctly should the venv/packages update without any
  associated config changes

NOTE: The reason why we compare local and remote checksum is to avoid
      unnecessarily downloading the venv when the checksums are in fact
      the same.  On small deploys this is more or less a non-issue but
      if a deploy w/ thousands of compute nodes re-runs playbooks we
      want to limit the venv downloads when it's unnecessary.

Change-Id: If11ba2b2183a89852d05880e67e98e334a2c947f
'}]
commit_message:
Re-deploy the Ceilometer venv if it mismatches the repo

We currently have two issues with venvs:

- if you update your venv on the repo server, it is not possible for
  that updated venv to land on the service's container as the get_url
  task always skips if the file exists (even if the file is different)
- if you have an updated venv on the repo server and forcefully delete
  the cached venv tarball on the service's container, the new tarball
  will get unarchived over top of the existing venv

This commit does the following:

- gets the checksum of the /var/cache tarball and downloads checksum
  file from repo server
- updates "Attempt venv download" to only download the venv if the
  cache doesn't exist or if the local and remote checksums differ
- adds a "force: true" to "Attempt venv download" task so that the venv
  tarball will get re-downloaded when the when condition is true (this
  is necessary otherwise the download will get skipped since the
  destination already exists)
- adds a new task "Remove existing venv" so we can first remove the
  venv before we unarchive the potentially new venv from the repo
  server
- updates "Create ceilometer venv dir" and "Unarchive pre-built venv"
  tasks to only proceed if "ceilometer_get_venv | changed", which
  prevents these tasks from running when they the venv tarball hasn't
  changed
- adds multiple service restarts to
  os_ceilometer/tasks/ceilometer_install.yml so that ceilometer will
  restart correctly should the venv/packages update without any
  associated config changes

NOTE: The reason why we compare local and remote checksum is to avoid
      unnecessarily downloading the venv when the checksums are in fact
      the same.  On small deploys this is more or less a non-issue but
      if a deploy w/ thousands of compute nodes re-runs playbooks we
      want to limit the venv downloads when it's unnecessary.

Change-Id: If11ba2b2183a89852d05880e67e98e334a2c947f

commit_message:
Make TripleO puppet check jobs voting

These are all green now, modulo the regression referenced in the
dependency below, so we can switch these jobs voting to avoid folks
ignoring the results.

Note that these jobs are also added to the gate queue, the unit
and style tests should be fast enough to run on gating, but we
don't want to re-run check-tripleo-jobs because these functional
tests take a long time to run.

Depends-On: I3cdcca6364476b324249a778d5e75a8befa26dff
Change-Id: Ida4aebcf5bebb8f83e6d446ef8db4dea56cc855f

commit_message:
Implement 'get-me-a-network' API building block

This patch introduces an API to allocate an externally connected
private tenant network on demand. The API is idempotent in that,
once the topology is provisioned, further API calls keep returning
the same topology to the caller.

The API, as introduced by the patch, is not currently on, and its
design carefully ensures minimal impact on the existing codebase.
In fact the feature depends on and enhances the external-net extension,
but it does so via callbacks.

A subsequent patch in this series will make it available by default,
and API tests will be added to validate the functionality.

Partially-implements: blueprint get-me-a-network

Co-Authored-By: Armando Migliaccio <armamig@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Henry Gessau <HenryG@gessau.net>

Change-Id: I4abd45252026431452f0d2cb2805043489c2f6ad

subject: Re-deploy the Swift venv if it mismatches the repo
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-01-29 02:04:12.000000000', 'files': ['playbooks/roles/os_swift/defaults/main.yml', 'playbooks/roles/os_swift/tasks/swift_install.yml'], 'message': 'Re-deploy the Swift venv if it mismatches the repo

We currently have two issues with venvs:

- if you update your venv on the repo server, it is not possible for
  that updated venv to land on the service's container as the get_url
  task always skips if the file exists (even if the file is different)
- if you have an updated venv on the repo server and forcefully delete
  the cached venv tarball on the service's container, the new tarball
  will get unarchived over top of the existing venv

This commit does the following:

- gets the checksum of the /var/cache tarball and downloads checksum
  file from repo server
- updates "Attempt venv download" to only download the venv if the
  cache doesn't exist or if the local and remote checksums differ
- adds a "force: true" to "Attempt venv download" task so that the venv
  tarball will get re-downloaded when the when condition is true (this
  is necessary otherwise the download will get skipped since the
  destination already exists)
- adds a new task "Remove existing venv" so we can first remove the
  venv before we unarchive the potentially new venv from the repo
  server
- updates "Create swift venv dir" and "Unarchive pre-built venv"
  tasks to only proceed if "swift_get_venv | changed", which
  prevents these tasks from running when they the venv tarball hasn't
  changed
- adds multiple service restarts to
  os_swift/tasks/swift_install.yml so that swift will restart
  correctly should the venv/packages update without any associated
  config changes

NOTE: The reason why we compare local and remote checksum is to avoid
      unnecessarily downloading the venv when the checksums are in fact
      the same.  On small deploys this is more or less a non-issue but
      if a deploy w/ thousands of compute nodes re-runs playbooks we
      want to limit the venv downloads when it's unnecessary.

Change-Id: I4b028f6e4ca59eceac010d2bbc10a8d79f6f3937
(cherry picked from commit 1bb51c2cb358206fdc7e02aeba8abc081f317ef9)
'}]
commit_message:
Re-deploy the Swift venv if it mismatches the repo

We currently have two issues with venvs:

- if you update your venv on the repo server, it is not possible for
  that updated venv to land on the service's container as the get_url
  task always skips if the file exists (even if the file is different)
- if you have an updated venv on the repo server and forcefully delete
  the cached venv tarball on the service's container, the new tarball
  will get unarchived over top of the existing venv

This commit does the following:

- gets the checksum of the /var/cache tarball and downloads checksum
  file from repo server
- updates "Attempt venv download" to only download the venv if the
  cache doesn't exist or if the local and remote checksums differ
- adds a "force: true" to "Attempt venv download" task so that the venv
  tarball will get re-downloaded when the when condition is true (this
  is necessary otherwise the download will get skipped since the
  destination already exists)
- adds a new task "Remove existing venv" so we can first remove the
  venv before we unarchive the potentially new venv from the repo
  server
- updates "Create swift venv dir" and "Unarchive pre-built venv"
  tasks to only proceed if "swift_get_venv | changed", which
  prevents these tasks from running when they the venv tarball hasn't
  changed
- adds multiple service restarts to
  os_swift/tasks/swift_install.yml so that swift will restart
  correctly should the venv/packages update without any associated
  config changes

NOTE: The reason why we compare local and remote checksum is to avoid
      unnecessarily downloading the venv when the checksums are in fact
      the same.  On small deploys this is more or less a non-issue but
      if a deploy w/ thousands of compute nodes re-runs playbooks we
      want to limit the venv downloads when it's unnecessary.

Change-Id: I4b028f6e4ca59eceac010d2bbc10a8d79f6f3937
(cherry picked from commit 1bb51c2cb358206fdc7e02aeba8abc081f317ef9)

Port FileLikeIter and _MultipartMimeFileLikeObject and
swift.common.utils to Python 3:

* Update unit FileLikeIter tests to use byte strings.

Change-Id: Ibacddb70b22f624ecd83e374749578feddf8bca8
"}]
commit_message:
Port FileLikeIter to Python 3

Port FileLikeIter and _MultipartMimeFileLikeObject and
swift.common.utils to Python 3:

* Add a __next__() alias to the next() method. On Python 3, the
  next() method is no more used, __next__() is required.
* Use literal byte strings: FileLikeIter _MultipartMimeFileLikeObject
  are written to handle binary files.
* test_close(): replace .FileLikeIter('abcdef') with
  FileLikeIter([b'a', b'b', b'c']). On Python 3, list(b'abc') returns
  [97, 98, 99], whereas ['a', 'b', 'c'] is returned on Python 2.
* Update unit FileLikeIter tests to use byte strings.

Change-Id: Ibacddb70b22f624ecd83e374749578feddf8bca8

commit_message:
Context Picker should inherit BS dropdown styles

The first step in the dynamic theme effort requires that the context
selection picker inherit properly from a dropdown menu, so that the
styles can be shared and the experience is matched.

Dynamic themes will use the 'select' experience of the context menu
but from within the user menu, so it was necessary to match the
experiences to minimize duplicated code.

The style of the context menu was extremely dependant on DOM structure
and therefore difficult to customize. This has been simplified by using
classes and attempting to keep specificity as low as possible.

Change-Id: Idb9e8f5c1d246688418f68e12fb53f094c01ea34
Partially-implements: blueprint horizon-dynamic-theme
Partially-Implements: blueprint bootstrap-html-standards

commit_message:
L3: enable plugin to decide if subnet is mandatory

Commit 07077bebb69da29994257d061d3a8d7ea9598c3d removed
enforcing that a subnet should be defined on a network. In
the case of IPv6 this is cool, but for V4 it is problematic.

The patch adds in a callback that enables the plugin to
determine validation policy.

The callback will be invoked prior to creating the gateway
port.

Closes-bug: #1543012

Change-Id: Idb7eeb5e0071aa5a2f302fba083504c4582edc1a

[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-02-07 22:44:31.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/unit/api/openstack/compute/test_api.py'], 'message': 'Top 100 slow tests: api.openstack.compute.test_api

Three of the api tests show up in the top 100 slow unit tests:

    http://paste.openstack.org/show/485806/

These tests create a bunch fake WSGI apps, each costing as much as 0.5
seconds. This patch reduces the cost of creating those fakes by using
the init_only option, and stubbing out extension loading. It also
reduces the number of fakes created (see ncalls).

$ tox -e py27 nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.compute.test_api.APITest

Before:

   total runtime: 18.5453 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       24    0.001    0.000    9.752    0.406 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       12    0.000    0.000    6.445    0.537 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

After:

   total runtime: 0.8630 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        3    0.000    0.000    0.051    0.017 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        3    0.000    0.000    0.064    0.021 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

Change-Id: Ie56e0f3dbdab4b6324c152915dfad5ae668a3fe9
'}]
commit_message:
Top 100 slow tests: api.openstack.compute.test_api

Three of the api tests show up in the top 100 slow unit tests:

    http://paste.openstack.org/show/485806/

These tests create a bunch fake WSGI apps, each costing as much as 0.5
seconds. This patch reduces the cost of creating those fakes by using
the init_only option, and stubbing out extension loading. It also
reduces the number of fakes created (see ncalls).

$ tox -e py27 nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.compute.test_api.APITest

Before:

   total runtime: 18.5453 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       24    0.001    0.000    9.752    0.406 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       12    0.000    0.000    6.445    0.537 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

After:

   total runtime: 0.8630 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        3    0.000    0.000    0.051    0.017 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        3    0.000    0.000    0.064    0.021 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

Change-Id: Ie56e0f3dbdab4b6324c152915dfad5ae668a3fe9

commit_message:
libvirt: Make behavior of os_require_quiesce consistent

Currently, os_require_quiesce metadata is used in two meanings.
For volume backed instances, quiescing is always tried on
snapshot, and the metadata specifies whether snapshot should
be aborted if quiescing is failed. For image backed instances
in the libvirt driver, the metadata determines whether quiescing
is invoked or not.

To make the behaviors consistent, this introduces the same logic
as volume backed instances into libvirt image snapshotting.

This also fixes AttributeError during live snapshot introduced by
commit 4f43bbafa4bfc2ab149d5db4eb55320c1602658b.

Change-Id: Iade076c996118e53d085ede9574cdf01c9e97829
Closes-Bug: #1436579
Closes-Bug: #1488565

commit_message:
Log more info when mke2fs fails on a guest

We have a device not found issue, but it's unclear if the device
doesn't exist at all, or it's in the wrong place. When we fail, dump
out the contents of /dev for further review.

Change-Id: I8b66b8acadc1d50a5ea7befd5ca6874c1dedcb4e

commit_message:
Top 100 slow tests: api.openstack.compute.test_volumes

The volume tests are slow. They account for 7 of the top 100 slow unit
tests:

    http://paste.openstack.org/show/485806/

These tests create a bunch fake WSGI apps, each costing as much as 0.6
seconds. This patch reduces the cost of creating those fakes by using
the init_only option. It also reduces the number of fake WSGI apps
created (see ncalls).

$ tox -e py27 nova.tests.unit.api.openstack.compute.test_volumes

Before:

   total runtime: 20.9060 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       22    0.001    0.000    1.891    0.086 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
       10    0.000    0.000    6.020    0.602 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

After:

   total runtime: 7.0804 sec

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        9    0.000    0.000    0.297    0.033 fakes.py:67(wsgi_app)

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        7    0.000    0.000    0.470    0.067 fakes.py:89(wsgi_app_v21)

Change-Id: I87845cd2c514c64e42201c7b99381ea63635afe7

commit_message:
pip install -r requirements.txt is not necessary in Ubuntu 14.04

On Ubuntu 14.04, when you run python setup.py from the directory
of Swift, the setuptools will parse requirements.txt and install
packages if needed.

Please note, thanks to the good advices by Kota Tsuyuzaki, the
purpuse of this commit have changed.

Change-Id: I1537791759e5df749afa8fb48f580471c8e539bd

commit_message:
Allow user-data on amphora creation

Currently, Amphora configuration data is being sent as personality
files as considered by Nova and some providers have limitations
and must use cloud-init user-data.

This patch introduces a new config option to enable user-data.
If enabled the files that were built, such as the amphora config
and certificates for the agent, will be templated into a cloud-init
user-data script that loads the files as expected. After this we
need to restart the agent as cloud-init happens at a higher level
than service scripts. This does increase the boot time.

This is configurable so there is no impact if it's not needed.

Change-Id: I60fa87722302eee9d3d1fd6ff1b5b5b697a2406e
Closes-Bug: #1541231

commit_message:
Introducing parallel zoning

The main purpose of this is spec to introduce parallel zoning capability
for the ZoneManager, in order to support unique switch type combinations.
The efficiency of zoning would be improved over the current method of
sequential zoning.

Change-Id: Icdf5d43b0c341bffd108ac8c9c0e70cd6054a254
blueprint: zonemanager-parallel-zoning

commit_message:
Grouping Multi Backend Pool Aware Cinder Scheduler

In a multi backend scenario a user should be able to specify
specific list of backend providers with pool info which cinder
scheduler should use during volume creation.

This proposal is to allow users to specify a list of backend providers
along with the pool information in the volume_type for the scheduler
to pick from. This helps in efficient cinder scheduling based on
user defined volume properties.

Change-Id: I04a4a3f101af3b3e34c3e10b6418a352a815fe2c
